replyContent: Hi there, thanks a lot for the feedback. I've released a new update to fix the late game problems, namely capping the lots to $300,000 each and allowing the player to gain cash from rocket launches. I agree the late game lots were too expensive and I hope this will alleviate those issues! - Thanks, Bobby

I'm sure this is a game for someone, but just not me.

i have avoided city sims since the 90s because they're always so hectic and micro-managey. Pocket City streamlines it into an exceptionally casual system. Excellent controls, minus a couple quality-of-life features like the missing ability to quickly repeat the last build option (would be useful for roads). A helpful (and thankfully brief) tutorial gets you right into the action. Relaxing audio. No time pressure - just build, rebuild, etc., at your own pace (especially if you disable natural disasters). Multiple levels of graphics quality and battery-saving options. Works in both landscape and portrait, but requires manually switching (does not auto-rotate). Plays very well on a 10-inch tablet (haven't tried it on a phone-sized screen). A pause button which lets us scroll around and examine the city at our leisure (e.g. to locate that elusive cat tribe) would be welcomed but is not a big deal.

This is a Sim City type game that, while basic in nature, has goals and progressive difficulty as the city becomes larger. A tutorial is included to show controls and concepts. As with all mobile app games, details can be difficult to see but the designer did provide an easy "zoom" to compensate. The game also has a "sandbox" option to allow all buildings and features to be used with unlimited money. A unique feature includes natural disasters and special events that can impact demographics.

replyContent: Hi there, thanks for the feedback. Generally, money is made when citizens are happy and there are sufficient commercial zones. You can view your income metrics in the Stats view. You collect income primarily through sales taxes in the early stage of the game. Hope that helps!

I found ways around them and if you don't think about your city's growth, then it will be mindless and there will be negative consequences from poor planning.

replyContent: Hi there, thank you for the review! To transfer your free city, go to the free app and in the Settings menu (top right gear icon) you can upload your city to the cloud. It will show you a code that you can use on the paid app to download your city. Thank you for playing!

+2 stars for having no ads or in-app purchases. It's nice to just buy and play without worrying about that stuff.  But the game was just so EASY. If you have any experience at all with city management games, like SimCity or Cities:Skylines, you will NOT find a challenge here.  There should be a higher difficulty option or some scenarios to try out.   I played it for a long time mostly because I wanted to see if it got more involved during the endgame phase, but it really didn't. It's just more of the same, but bigger.    You'll be making money more quickly than you can possibly spend, and it will fill up to your cash limit in a matter of seconds. You can raise this limit by building and upgrading banks later on, but you'll still never be strapped for cash. During my entire playthrough (all the way up to level 80 something) I never once struggled with anything.   I always had a surplus of money and it was always easy to keep the citizens happy.   Even the natural disasters don't really do anything; you get 100% of their damage as an insurance payout and you can instantly repair it by clicking one button in the damage report.

An absolute bargain of a game and, unlike SimCity BuildIt, it won't (attempt to) bleed you dry via (not so) micro-transactions. Admittedly, it's not as pretty as its overcommercialised cousin, but it compensates for that tenfold by not frustrating progress with inhibitors like City Storage and manual, wait-based production. The dynamics of this game are thus very different. For example, you can unlock all of the land expansion in a single day by temporarily cranking taxes up sky high and buying a new plot every time your bank accrues enough cash, which happens in real time. I'm not sure how long the game will retain my interest. All BuildIt content is unlocked by L40, but it looks as if this game has been designed to keep rewarding the long-time player.

This is a quite engaging city building game, well worth the upfront cost given how much time I sank into it. My only gripes are with the expert/hardest difficulty and how you need to actively fight the leveling system to survive. Leveling up increases your costs and decreases your citizens' happiness, reducing your tax revenues. Trying to increase revenue by building more doesn't work because food import costs will bleed you dry until you unlock farms at level 15. Thus you have to avoid any leveling for as long as possible, which is somewhat counterintuitive. But! This only matters if you are a hardcore min-maxer. In other modes you can just chill and build and throw block parties for your peeps!

Such a breath of fresh air. Finally a game in a market that heavily relies on extorting consumers that doesn't do such things! Download the free version for a demo (with ads that are done right) to see how you feel about the game, then pay the small amount for the premium version, then, guess what? You don't then have to pay even more to progress through the game, the price tag you see is the price you pay, no more. It's a fairly in-depth city builder game that you can play through without worrying about being pushed to pay extra, and you don't have to worry about ridiculous wait times either, you can progress exponentially with each time you play, not having to wait 24hrs+ for a single upgrade. And there's also a sandbox mode for those who are a little more creative, which is something almost all mobile city builders lack (because how else would they get people to pay for premium currency at premium prices?) I would highly recommend this game to anyone looking for a city sim.

First thing: this is the best city management game I've come across on Android. You get all the content at buy-in, and there are no arbitrary wait times. You're just playing a game at your own pace. However- if you're familiar from other games how to build a city for capacity, profitability, and service availability then you will quickly master the workings of this game. Do you know already that you want lots of parks, bus stops, and 2x2 lots? You know how to play. It is still fun! It's a neat mobile garden to tend. It would be great to see more varied ways to build districts, better traffic modeling, and upgrade paths for buildings, and be able to budget more precisely- but this is a mobile game. Those things are a wish list for the sequel that I hope comes from this. If you're a long-time fan of city builders this is a fun game that you'll quickly master. If you are new to them or introducing them to someone new this is fantastic. Either way I believe you'll get your money's worth.

This is it. This is The Dream come true -- a proper City Builder on your phone or tablet. None of this half-baked, time-gated, loot-box rubbish, just the pure, addicting gameplay you've loved all the way from Sim City to Cities: Skylines. There's nothing childish or dumbed-down about this game, but it still has the easy, light Sim City-style humour, backed up with what seem like pretty deep systems and as much intelligence in the design and AI as you could reasonably expect from a mobile phone-sized game. Structurally, it takes the best idea from the old Facebook Sim City (purchasable land expansions) and marries it to a beguiling graphical style that still makes sense at multiple zooms. Lots of options for balancing the graphics and gameplay with battery consumption, but even on the default 'medium' settings, it takes very little from my old Huaweii, even after 20-30 minutes.  Honestly, I played the Free version for 5 minutes then bought the full version right away. An excellent, excellent game, made with care and attention. The developers deserve to be rewarded with a purchase, especially so given the complete absence of cash-traps and time-sinks!

Really is exactly what everyone was looking for in a city building sim, the 
art and graphics are great, nice and quaint. The controls are smooth and 
the logistics of the game seem well balanced. Best of all, No Micro 
Transactions! And theres no balloon popping bullux that you find in the 
other games. I HATED having to keep up in all the factories full, ect. It 
was a chore. This game is a true city building sim and it's really done 
well. Very polished. The only issue I have with the game is its 
ridiculously easy. Even on expert mode, the money just pours in. It's hard 
to spend it all fast enough! After buying all the remaining land, there was 
nothing to dump it all on, and after filling the map there seemed to be no 
challange whatsoever. Even the disasters come with a hotfix button and you 
get all the money lost from damage instantly replaced by FEMA. It even 
auto-rebuilds the damaged zones for you. Why bother have the disasters then?

I bought this game mainly to show support for a game with integrity. I am also comfortable letting my kids play the game, knowing they won't be constantly nagged to buy things, or intentionally frustrated by the game to make them want to spend money. replyContent: From the free version, you can upload your city to the cloud in the settings section and get a code, which you can use to download on the paid version. Hope that helps!

This game should be considered the standard for mobile gaming, no 
microtransactions, brilliant pixel graphics and fun to play. Kudos to the 
dev
Saw it on Reddit played the free version and had to cop it

Playing on my Huawei tablet for a few hours and its great. Fortunately not 
experiencing any of the crashing others have reported. Was initially turned 
off by the low quality resolution but I was able to fix that in the 
settings. Really great game!
Perfect
Thank you, man!

Experienced a couple crashes, but the game has a lot of potential. If the 
dev can patch the game to reduce crashes it will be one of the better games 
on Android.
Awesome game! Crashes every 5 mins. Not a big deal but kinda annoying. S8+

Thanks for all your hardwork and providing us with a microtransaction free 
city builder on mobile. :)
Really like this game. Thanks codebrew games for a great city builder

I've been waiting for this for awhile now. City builder without iaps? Yes 
please.
